# Orchestrator Toolbox

This is the command catalog for Claude orchestrators. Read it before running a
round, assigning panes, or opening a gate window.

## Beads And Triage

- `bv --robot-triage --format toon`: first triage view. Use it to see ready
  work, blockers, graph-important recommendations, and suggested commands.
- `bv --robot-next`: minimal next-action view when you only need the top ready
  candidate.
- `br show <id> --json`: inspect the current tracker record before claiming or
  closing.
- `br update <id> --status in_progress`: claim work after confirming it is the
  intended bead.
- `br close <id> --reason "<commit/evidence refs>"`: close only after the
  commit, attestation, and verifier evidence exist.
- `br sync --flush-only`: export tracker state to `.beads/issues.jsonl` before
  staging tracker changes.

Do not parse `.beads/issues.jsonl` by hand for scheduling. Use `bv` for graph
triage and `br` for state changes.

## NTM Robot Surface

Use robot-readable commands only. Bare `ntm` can open an interactive UI.

- `ntm --robot-capabilities`: confirm supported robot actions before any
  state-changing NTM command.
- `ntm --robot-snapshot`: capture sessions, panes, identities, attention state,
  and current pane numbering.
- `ntm --robot-tail=<session> --panes=<pane>`: inspect recent pane output as
  liveness context only; tails are not completion evidence.
- `ntm --robot-activity`: inspect live activity when a snapshot is not enough
  to decide whether a pane is active.
- `ntm --robot-send=<session> --panes=<pane> --type=prompt --msg-file=<path>`:
  send a durable, file-backed wake or prompt after the mail/file context exists.
- `ntm add <session> N:<model>:<effort>`: spawn deliberately. Choose effort by
  task type: `xhigh` for critical-path implementers, `high` for judgment-cell
  verifiers, and `medium` for mechanical verification, lookup, and inventory.

Pane numbers can change after `ntm add`. Never rely on stale pane numbers. Use
PID-diff identification or a fresh `ntm --robot-snapshot` before every send,
then verify the target pane identity again after the send.

If the runtime ignores per-spawn effort, use the config-default swap workaround:
temporarily change the Codex template default effort, spawn the pane, then
restore the default. Record the workaround and the intended `model:effort` in
the dispatch note.

## Agent Mail

Register before work and open the expected contact mesh:

- `macro_start_session`: start the project session and register the identity.
- `register_agent`: lower-level registration when the macro is not available.
- `set_contact_policy open`: use immediately after registration when the round
  needs worker/verifier/orchestrator contact.
- `respond_contact`: approve expected pending requests when operating in a
  policy that requires pairwise approval.
- `fetch_inbox` and `fetch_topic`: read durable dispatch, verifier packets, and
  replies.
- `send_message`: send claim notices, verifier packets, handoffs, and blockers.
- `file_reservation_paths` and `release_file_reservations`: reserve exact paths
  before edits and release after commit, abort, or handoff.

If an identity resets, register again first, then open contact policy again.
State the old-to-new identity continuity in the completion or verdict body.

## Burpvalve Gate And Verifier Flow

- `burpvalve hash --staged`: compute the staged payload hash before verifier
  packets.
- `burpvalve verifier begin`: create the responses binding for the exact
  staged payload.
- `burpvalve verifier prompts --json`: regenerate packet text for the current
  responses binding and staged diff.
- `burpvalve verifier submit`: submit a verdict only for cells actually
  inspected in a separate context.
- `burpvalve commit --responses <file> --agent <name> --model <model>`: run the
  commit gate with the verifier evidence file named explicitly.

Verifier provenance must be truthful:

- `kind`: for pane/subagent review use `independent_subagent`; use
  `main_agent` only when policy allows and the main agent really performed the
  check.
- `agent`: Agent Mail identity or the named native subagent.
- `model`: actual model used for the verifier context.
- `runtime`: include the surface, pane/subagent, and any identity-continuity
  facts needed to audit the verdict.
- `separate_context`: `true` only when the verifier actually had a separate
  context.

Verdicts are not vibes. Use `pass` for satisfied conditions, `not_applicable`
when the condition truly does not apply and evidence explains why, `fail` for a
real blocker, and `unknown` when the verifier could not complete the check.

## Monitoring Patterns

Use the shipped scripts as the required monitoring method. Ad-hoc polling needs
a stated reason in the handoff.

- `scripts/poll_worker.py`: monitor a worker pane. It treats `Working (`,
  `Waiting for background terminal`, and `esc to interrupt` as busy markers,
  requires consecutive quiet polls before calling a pane idle, and declares
  completion only from the evidence artifact named in the dispatch.
- `scripts/poll_round.py`: monitor a verifier responses file. It emits pending
  counts, detects unchanged pending counts, can send proactive round
  announcements, and can auto-wake stuck panes.

Both scripts emit JSONL structured events. Default mode is report/dry-run;
`--execute` is required for looped polling or terminal wakes.

Round announcements should name the work unit, responses file or artifact,
pane assignments, exact condition split, and the required completion phrase.
Auto-wakes should point to the durable artifact or Agent Mail thread, not paste
large instructions into the terminal.
